Continuous Integration Using OpenShift Lab

This lab illustrates software life cycle management using continuous integration (CI) tools in an OpenShift deployment environment. You become familiar with CI in this environment using an application based on Node.js.

Many tools can provide Continuous Integration and Delivery (CI/CD). The intent of this lab is to demonstrate the flexibility of the image-based approach of Jenkins (see https://jenkins-ci.org) and OpenShift.

Goal

  • Use CI tools in an OpenShift deployment environment while building a JavaScript/Node.js application

Credits

  • Much of the content comes from the Jenkins image for OpenShift (https://github.com/openshift/jenkins.git), created by the Red Hat OpenShift core engineering team.

Workflow

This diagram shows the sequence of CI events executed by the various components used in the lab:

  • Developer commits change to application source code and pushes to Git repository (in GitHub)

  • Jenkins polls Git repository and detects change

  • Jenkins pulls latest code from Git repository

  • Jenkins executes application builds in the following order:

    • Project workspace cleaned

    • Project compiled

    • Project unit tests executed

  • Jenkins triggers BuildConfig object of OpenShift S2I project

  • S2I process pulls latest source code from Git repository in GitHub

    In the case of a Node.js application, there is no runtime artifact built from the project and deployed to OpenShift. As a result, there is nothing for Jenkins to pass to the S2I build. In the next lab, you see how Jenkins makes a Java Web Archive (WAR), or *.war file, available to S2I.

  • OpenShift deploys built image from S2I to an OpenShift node

1. Create hello-nodejs OpenShift Objects

In this section, you create a new Node.js application called hello-nodejs, launch it, add a route to the web service, and verify that the application is running.

  1. On your client workstation, open a terminal window.

  2. If your current OpenShift client session has expired, re-authenticate with the OpenShift master, using oc login, to generate a valid session, as discussed in Java EE Application Deployment Lab.

  3. Using the command line, delete the resources you created:

    $ $HOME/ocp-appdev-labs/admin/purge_apps.sh

  4. Using the out-of-the-box OpenShift Node.js image stream, create the OpenShift objects that make up the hello-nodejs application:

    $ oc new-app nodejs:latest~https://github.com/wkulhanek/ocp-appdev-helloworld-nodejs.git --strategy=source --name=hello-nodejs

--> Found image 448a51d (5 weeks old) in image stream "nodejs" in project "openshift" under tag "latest" for "nodejs:latest"

    Node.js 4
    ---------
    Platform for building and running Node.js 4 applications

    Tags: builder, nodejs, nodejs4

    * A source build using source code from https://github.com/wkulhanek/ocp-appdev-helloworld-nodejs.git will be created
      * The resulting image will be pushed to image stream "hello-nodejs:latest"
      * Use 'start-build' to trigger a new build
    * This image will be deployed in deployment config "hello-nodejs"
    * Port 8080/tcp will be load balanced by service "hello-nodejs"
      * Other containers can access this service through the hostname "hello-nodejs"

--> Creating resources with label app=hello-nodejs ...
    imagestream "hello-nodejs" created
    buildconfig "hello-nodejs" created
    deploymentconfig "hello-nodejs" created
    service "hello-nodejs" created
--> Success
    Build scheduled, use 'oc logs -f bc/hello-nodejs' to track its progress.
    Run 'oc status' to view your app.

  5. Execute the oc get pod command about every 10 seconds until the build pod’s STATUS shows Completed:

    $ oc get pod
NAME                   READY     STATUS      RESTARTS   AGE
hello-nodejs-1-build   0/1       Completed   0          3m
hello-nodejs-1-ddt2f   1/1       Running     0          2m

  6. Add a route to the hello-nodejs service:

    $ oc expose service/hello-nodejs
route "hello-nodejs" exposed

  7. Determine the URL to your hello-nodejs application:

    $ oc get route
NAME           HOST/PORT                                                 PATH      SERVICES       PORT       TERMINATION   WILDCARD
hello-nodejs   hello-nodejs-wkocpappdev.apps.na1.openshift.opentlc.com             hello-nodejs   8080-tcp                 None

  8. Test the hello-nodejs application, substituting your route URL for <hello-nodejs URL>:

    curl <hello-nodejs URL>

  9. Verify that you see an OK response.

    From now on, you use Jenkins to build and deploy this application.

  10. To make sure that only Jenkins will trigger a new deployment, turn off the auto deployment after a build option:

    $ oc set triggers dc/hello-nodejs --remove-all

2. Explore OpenShift API Security

Jenkins communicates with the OpenShift master node API to trigger a build and check status. This section discusses the security features that allow the client in Jenkins to interact with the OpenShift master node. In this section, you grant permissions to the serviceaccount project. The Jenkins container running in your OpenShift project triggers the S2I build process of the hello-nodejs application. This occurs when you kick off a pipeline in Jenkins. Jenkins interacts with the master node REST API.

Jenkins authenticates using the following OpenShift service account:

system:serviceaccount:<your OpenShift project>:default

  1. Grant administrative privileges to the default service account of your project using the oc policy command:

    oc policy add-role-to-user admin system:serviceaccount:<your OpenShift Project Name>:default
    If you do not remember your project name, use oc get projects to view all your available projects.

    • The default service account requires these privileges in order to trigger an S2I build.

  2. Describe the roles assigned to the default service account:

    oc describe policyBindings :default

    • The default service account is now assigned a role of admin.

    • This role grants all permissions to this service account, including permission to trigger an S2I build.

3. Create Jenkins Container

For this lab, a Jenkins container runs within the scope of your OpenShift project. In this section, you set up the environment to run this Jenkins container.

  1. On your workstation, start the Jenkins container with a 2 GB persistent volume claim and a 2 GB value for requested memory limit:

    $ oc new-app jenkins-persistent -p MEMORY_LIMIT=2Gi -p VOLUME_CAPACITY=2Gi -p ENABLE_OAUTH=false
--> Deploying template "openshift/jenkins-persistent" to project wkocpappdev

     Jenkins (Persistent)
     ---------
     Jenkins service, with persistent storage.

NOTE: You must have persistent volumes available in your cluster to use this template.

     A Jenkins service has been created in your project.  Log into Jenkins with your OpenShift account.  The tutorial at https://github.com/openshift/origin/blob/master/examples/jenkins/README.md contains more information about using this template.

     * With parameters:
        * Jenkins Service Name=jenkins
        * Jenkins JNLP Service Name=jenkins-jnlp
        * Enable OAuth in Jenkins=false
        * Memory Limit=2Gi
        * Volume Capacity=2Gi
        * Jenkins ImageStream Namespace=openshift
        * Jenkins ImageStreamTag=jenkins:latest

--> Creating resources ...
    route "jenkins" created
    persistentvolumeclaim "jenkins" created
    deploymentconfig "jenkins" created
    serviceaccount "jenkins" created
    rolebinding "jenkins_edit" created
    service "jenkins-jnlp" created
    service "jenkins" created
--> Success
    Run 'oc status' to view your app.
    While the current project does not need 2 GB memory, the Java EE project in the next lab does.

  2. Execute the oc get pod command about every 10 seconds until the your Jenkins pod’s STATUS shows Running and 1/1 for READY:

    $ oc get pods
NAME                   READY     STATUS      RESTARTS   AGE
hello-nodejs-1-build   0/1       Completed   0          11m
hello-nodejs-1-bw51f   1/1       Running     0          10m
jenkins-1-ffq19        1/1       Running     0          2m

    If your Jenkins deployment fails, it is most likely because the initial startup took longer than allowed by the liveness probe in the Jenkins template. If that happens you must edit the initialDelaySeconds timeout of the livenessProbe in the Jenkins deployment configuration. The default is 120 seconds. Try increasing it to 500 seconds:

    $ oc set probe dc jenkins --readiness --initial-delay-seconds=500

    If the deployment continues to fail, increase the timeout again. After patching the updated deployment configuration, it triggers a new deployment with the updated livenessProbe.

4. Log In to Jenkins Container

Once the Jenkins pod is Running, you use your browser to log in to the Jenkins web application.

  1. Determine the new route to your Jenkins web application:

    $ oc get route
NAME           HOST/PORT                                                 PATH      SERVICES       PORT       TERMINATION     WILDCARD
hello-nodejs   hello-nodejs-wkocpappdev.apps.na1.openshift.opentlc.com             hello-nodejs   8080-tcp                   None
jenkins        jenkins-wkocpappdev.apps.na1.openshift.opentlc.com                  jenkins        <all>      edge/Redirect   None

  2. Note the value of HOST/PORT, which is the URL to your Jenkins web application.

  3. Use your browser to navigate to this URL.

    • If you get a certificate security warning, accept it and continue.

  4. Log in to the Jenkins container with these credentials:

    • User: admin

    • Password: password

    • Expect to see the Jenkins dashboard:

5. Build Jenkins Projects

Earlier in this lab, you created OpenShift objects to support a hello-nodejs application running in OpenShift Container Platform.

In this section, you configure Jenkins to build and test the hello-nodejs application from source using a Jenkins pipeline. Once the application is built and tested, Jenkins can deploy the application to OpenShift and verify that the deployment is successful.

  1. On the Jenkins dashboard, click New Item to create a new Jenkins project.

    • Use hello-nodejs-pipeline for the Item name, and select Pipeline as the item type.

  2. Click OK to create the project.

  3. In the pipeline definition, make sure that Pipeline script is selected.

    • You use OpenShift, not Jenkins, to build the application. You are simply triggering the OpenShift build from the Jenkins pipeline.

      Pipelines in Jenkins are defined as Groovy scripts. The OpenShift default Jenkins image has all the right pipeline features already enabled. It also comes with the OpenShift plug-ins to call OpenShift actions from a pipeline. There are actions to build, deploy, verify the service, and much more.

  4. Enter the following pipeline script into the Script field:

    node {
  stage ("Build") {
    echo '*** Build Starting ***'
    openshiftBuild apiURL: 'https://openshift.default.svc.cluster.local', authToken: '', bldCfg: 'hello-nodejs', buildName: '', checkForTriggeredDeployments: 'false', commitID: '', namespace: '', showBuildLogs: 'false', verbose: 'false', waitTime: ''
    openshiftVerifyBuild apiURL: 'https://openshift.default.svc.cluster.local', authToken: '', bldCfg: 'hello-nodejs', checkForTriggeredDeployments: 'false', namespace: '', verbose: 'false'
    echo '*** Build Complete ***'
  }
  stage ("Deploy") {
    echo '*** Deployment Starting ***'
    openshiftDeploy apiURL: 'https://openshift.default.svc.cluster.local', authToken: '', depCfg: 'hello-nodejs', namespace: '', verbose: 'false', waitTime: ''
    openshiftVerifyDeployment apiURL: 'https://openshift.default.svc.cluster.local', authToken: '', depCfg: 'hello-nodejs', namespace: '', replicaCount: '1', verbose: 'false', verifyReplicaCount: 'false', waitTime: ''
    echo '*** Deployment Complete ***'
  }
  stage ("Verify") {
    echo '*** Service Verification Starting ***'
    openshiftVerifyService apiURL: 'https://openshift.default.svc.cluster.local', authToken: '', namespace: '', svcName: 'hello-nodejs', verbose: 'false'
    echo '*** Service Verification Complete ***'
  }
}

    • In this script note, you leave the namespace (project) blank because Jenkins is running in the same project as the target project.

    • Also notice the URL of the API endpoint (https://openshift.default.svc.cluster.local). This is an internal URL which also works because Jenkins is running inside the OpenShift cluster. If Jenkins is running somewhere outside the cluster, you need to provide the master URL as well as an authentication token.

  5. Click Save.

    • Expect this to return you to the project home screen.

      You create a pipeline with Build, Deploy, and Verify stages. Pipeline stages are defined using the stage keyword.

6. Trigger hello-nodejs-pipeline Build

In this section, you manually initiate a build of the hello-nodejs-pipeline Jenkins project to trigger it.

In a real-world environment, you set up build triggers to start the pipeline automatically—for example, when new code is pushed into the source code repository.

  1. Navigate to the hello-nodejs-pipeline project page.

  2. On the left, click Build Now.

    • In a couple of minutes, the project shows a graphical representation of the current pipeline:

    • The pipeline progresses through three stages-- Build, Deploy, and Verify service—until it is finished:

  3. On the left in the Build History box, click the latest build number to display the pipeline execution details.

  4. On the build details page, click Console Output to examine the progress of the pipeline in more detail.

  5. When you see that the build is finished, click Back to Project in the top left corner to return to the pipeline view.

    • Expect to see that all three stages of the pipeline are green including the displayed execution duration.

  6. Log out of the Jenkins console.

7. Delete hello-nodejs Objects

The Jenkins-related OpenShift objects are used in other labs of this course, but the hello-nodejs objects are not used again. In this section, you delete them.

  1. Delete the hello-nodejs objects:

    $ oc delete all -l app=hello-nodejs
